          <td valign="top">

<span class="txth1">plugin/fonts.vim : Multi OS Font Plugin</span> 

<br>
<br>

<!-- karma table -->
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="1" bordercolor="#000066">
<tr>
  <td class="lightbg"><b>&nbsp;script karma&nbsp;</b></td>
  <td>
    Rating <b>72/24</b>,
    Downloaded by 1727  </td>
  <td class="lightbg">
  <b>&nbsp;Comments, bugs, improvements&nbsp;</b>
  </td>
  <td>
    <a href="http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/Script:1337">Vim wiki</a>
  </td>  
</tr>
</table>
<p>

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
<tr><td class="prompt">created by</td></tr>
<tr><td><a href="/account/profile.php?user_id=7818">Martin Krischik</a></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">script type</td></tr>
<tr><td>utility</td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">description</td></tr>
<tr><td>This plug-in set's the font used depending on the operating system / windowing system used. It also contains a smaller and larger font to zoom in and out. It is very helpful if you use GVim with more then one OS, display resolutions etc. pp.<br><br>You can easily expand the plugin for more OS's or fonts.<br><br>Reports errors to: <a target="_blank" href="http://code.google.com/p/vim-scripts/issues/list">http://code.google.com/p/vim-scripts/issues/list</A><br>Discuss improvements on: <a target="_blank" href="http://groups.google.com/group/vim_scripts">http://groups.google.com/group/vim_scripts</A><br>For Support see: <a target="_blank" href="http://code.google.com/p/vim-scripts/wiki/MultiOSFontPlugin">http://code.google.com/p/vim-scripts/wiki/MultiOSFontPlugin</A><br></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">install details</td></tr>
<tr><td>Copy the file into your plug-in directory and edit to reflect fonts installed on your system(s).<br><br>If you don't know the fonts available on your system you have two Ways open:<br><br>1) The last &quot;Edit&quot; menu entry in GVim is &quot;Choose Font&quot;. Then it's easy: you choose a nice font and then use &quot;:set guifont&quot; to find out it's internal name.<br><br>2) The &quot;Choose Font&quot; Menu is available - AFAIK that happens with older XServer set-ups (like Motif)&nbsp;&nbsp;in which case you can use the xfontsel program&nbsp;&nbsp;to find out which fonts are available and what names they have.<br></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
</table>

